Autolog automatically shares your Origin ID, online presence, profile picture, friends list, and stats and activity with your cross platform friends. If you don't want to share this information, you can play offline.  The same information will be available to your cross platform friends on the Need for Speed™ Network, your destination for all things Need For Speed. Who can see your Network profile is governed by your Origin privacy settings. When you start playing Need for Speed™ Rivals your online status is visible to your cross platform friends on the Need for Speed™ Network map.

OverWatch is a mini game on the Need for Speed™ Network that allows players to help or hinder their Friends who are playing Need for Speed™ Rivals multiplayer sessions.  If you turn OverWatch off, you will remain visible to your Origin Friends on the Need for Speed™ world map, but they will not be able to use OverWatch to help or hinder you in your Need for Speed™ Rivals multiplayer sessions.   Turning OverWatch off will also mean that you cannot gain Fuel from playing Need for Speed™ Rivals to use in OverWatch. You can change this setting at any time.

After a video surfaced on the Internet last night of an illegal street racer outrunning the police in Redwood City, the video has since garnered millions of hits, and also prompted the police to increase their patrols.
What is especially remarkable about this story is that historically the underground racing community has maintained a low profile, avoiding drawing attention to themselves.
But since the video's release, dozens of other racers have begun posting their videos as well.
While underground racers have traditionally maintained a low profile, since a video of a racer outrunning a cop went viral last night, dozens of other racers have begun posting their videos as well.
Here's what our senior legal analyst had to say about this.
The thing you have to understand is that this isn't the Harlem Shake or a dancing baby.
These people are posting evidence of felony reckless driving which can be used against them in court.
The chief of police and the district attorney have very clear that they are investigating the videos and anyone they identify will be prosecuted to the full extent of the law.
The chief of police and the district attorney has been very clear that they are investigating the videos and anyone they identify will be prosecuted to the full extent of the law.
We are the truth, written in invisible ink.  The lost gospel of freedom.
They say Stockholm Syndrome is when victims begin to identify with their captors.
When you begin to accept, and even love the very people who oppress and abuse you.
If that's true, then this city is one massive experiment in Societal Stockholm Syndrome.
We are born free, resisting authority.
Daring to climb, to run, to follow our impulses. We defy the status quo, but then one day…we break.
Daring to climb, to run, to defy the status quo.  But then one day…we break.
We accept the illusion of authority.  We welcome their chains.
We pay them to impose the threat of violence because we'd rather have everyone shackled than risk seeing what others might do with their freedom – what would happen if we all still dared.
Philosophers have a name for this collective surrender of free will.  They call it the Social Contract.  But I never signed up for it.

Unlocked at Cop Rank {0:s}

As a Cop you can start Pursuits with any Racer at any time in any event. When you spot one, drive up close and turn on your sirens, or slam a Racer to activate them automatically.  Once started, if you spot more Racers they are automatically added to the Pursuit, and any Cops that cross paths with the Pursuit can join in.  Racers escape by putting distance between them and the Cops, and making sure the Cops can't see them.  Cops Bust Racers by forcing them to Wreck or performing Lockdowns.   Once started, you will find many EasyDrive functions unavailable until the Pursuit is over or you abandon it.

Flags flew at half-mast today as Officer John McManis was laid to rest at Woodlawn Cemetery.
A funeral procession of over one hundred cars ushered his body to its final resting place.
According to a spokesman for Redwood City PD, the police will not stop until the racers responsible for the death of the slain officer are brought to justice.
A funeral procession of over one hundred cars ushered the body of officer John McManis to its final resting place today.
According to a police spokesman, law enforcement will not stop until the racers responsible for the death of the slain officer are brought to justice.
If there is one lesson the police should learn from this, it's that they can't keep up with us.
Officer McManis pushed his limit, but ours was further.
We take no joy in his death, but it was he who chose to get in over his head.
They say we endanger the public, but they are the ones who aren't in control.
But they don't want the truth - they want blood.
They want revenge for a crime that was never committed.
It's an easier narrative than accepting that we are all responsible for our actions, and that both cops and racers take the risks we do because it rewards us with adrenaline and purpose.
The police were our rivals.  Now they are our enemies.
Any racer with a rational sense of self-preservation would get out of the game now, but they wouldn't have gotten into it in the first place if they did.

After a video of a street racer in Redwood City was posted online, dozens of other racers have begun uploading videos of their exploits as well.
After a video of a street racer was posted online, dozens of other racers have begun uploading copycat videos.
It appears that what was once an anonymous underground sport is now becoming a sort of viral reality show with racers embracing and even seeking out notoriety.
It's as if they're turning the streets of Redwood City into a Roman Circus for the 21st Century.
Perception is reality.
Law and order only exists as long as the public believes it.
Today they believe it less than yesterday.
They see racers defying the laws without consequence.
And when the laws no longer have teeth - when they become polite suggestions - society breaks down and we revert to our true nature - bellum omnium contra omnes.
The war of all against all.
We are the thin blue line protecting man from the chaos that is hardwired into their DNA.
The public accuses us of intimidation, but the truth is that show of force is preferable to use of force.
And when show of force isn't enough to maintain order, sometimes you have to settle for the real thing.

This is an open manifesto – a shout out to all racers in Redwood County and around the world.
I am not your enemy.  I am not a threat.
I am your rival.  I will not destroy you.
I will make you stronger. I will make you faster.  I will make you smarter.
I am not your friend.
And I am not your brother.
But I will make you drive harder.
I will challenge the boundaries of what you are capable of.
I will give you purpose.
And you will do the same for me.
We exist as a function of each other - a solar system in orbit, each planet pulling the others forward through the darkness.
There are those who seek to destroy us, and unless we accept that we only exist as a unit, then our system will collapse and the individuals will be cast out into the void.
I call on all racers to not allow our rivalry to divide us, but to draw strength from it - to band together to protect our way of life from our true enemies.
The police have called us a ‘network of racers', and classified us as an ‘organized criminal enterprise'.
Until today, this was a lie.
Until today, we were not organized and we were not a coordinated network of outlaws.
But today the lie becomes true.
We're coming to you live with breaking news.
Within the last hour, multiple news outlets received a video from a source claiming to be the notorious street racer Zephyr.
He says he is issuing an open challenge to all street racers and law enforcement.
In the video, he has posted a map with a 20-mile route where racers and cops can settle their rivalry once and for all.
While law enforcement is billing this as a declaration of war by the racing community, Zephyr claims it is, quote, 'the ultimate reality show.'
One thing is certain - anyone appearing on the race route during the posted time will be deemed a threat to public safety by law enforcement.

After numerous complaints from the public about police brutality, the U.S. Department of Justice has been called in to examine what is being called a culture of intimidation in the Redwood City police force.
Dozens of officers have been implicated in this growing scandal.
In the 18th precinct, which has been the epicenter of this investigation, all officers have been put on reduced duty while the investigation plays out.
In the precinct at the center of this scandal, all officers have been put on restricted duty while the investigation plays out.
Most of the officers have been assigned to administrative tasks, and what few officers remain on patrol are restricted to parking enforcement and observational duties.

In the meantime, the FBI Vehicle Response Team, which is the nation's top interdiction unit, has been called in to secure the streets and deal with the growing street-racing problem until local police are cleared of wrongdoing.
The VRT is typically only called upon to target violent criminal organizations or assist in Federal States of Emergency…

Welcome to All Drive, a unique new way to experience Need for Speed™.
All Drive allows you, your friends and other drivers to race and chase together, seamlessly, as you play through your Cop Assignments or Racer Speedlists.
To find out who is in your world check the map or look out for them out on the road – some will be Cops, others will be Racers.
You can route to other players by setting a waypoint to them on the map, through Easydrive, or by jumping straight to a nearby event from inside your garage.
AllDriving near another player will increase your speedpoints for everything you do; the bigger the group, the more your speedpoints will be increased.
All Drive also allows you to start events together, sharing any rewards and speedpoints you earn – simply pull up to the event start together and look out for the All Drive message.
You can also interact with your friends on the Need For Speed Network.

We tried to play by the rules, and where did that leave us?
Chained up on the side of the road like dogs, forced to watch as the racers mock us.
We used to rely on strength in unity, a brotherhood bound by honor – believing that in a just universe, justice would prevail.
It was a noble cause, but there is no nobility in failure.
If we want to win, we need to play by a new set of rules.
A different code. Our enemies operate outside the law - so too must we.
Instead of fighting them from the outside, we must fight them from the inside.
We will infiltrate their world.
Lone wolves in sheep's clothing.
The police have confiscated many of their vehicles, which sit idle in the impound lot.
Their potential untapped.
Now they will be our weapons of war.
Our Trojan Horse.
The sources on the street we have turned to for information will become our access agents, opening the door for us to pose as the enemy and get close enough to inflict devastating harm.
The racers will think we are their rivals, but we are the horsemen.
